{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_inman_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340582603/1913123001/1128.xml":{"full_text":"J\nA persistent\npurpose\nto produce\nperfect\nbiscuit\nNational Biscuit\nCompany is inspired\nby a persistent pur\npose to produce per\nfect biscuit and to de\nliver them in perfect\ncondition.\nThe accomplishment\nof this purpose has\nresulted in the build\ning of modern baker\nies, in the invention of\nnew machinery, in\nthe exercise of un-\nceasing care, in the\nselection of finest in\ngredients.\nThe perfect products\nof the National\nBiscuit Company\nare delivered toyou in\nperfect condition\u2014\nsome in packages\nwith the famous In\ner-seal Trade Mark,\nsome in attractive\nsmall tins and some\nfrom the familiar\nglass-front cans.\nBuy biscuit\nbaked by\nNATIONAL\nBISCUIT\nCOMPANY\nAlways look for that name\nPerfectly Simple\n\u201cYou see, my dear, it\u2019s like this,\"\npaid Robert Flemming, according to the\nChicago Itecord-Herald. \u201cWe will say\nthat I decide to speculate in corn. I\nhave $500 in cash. If I were* to actually\nbuy the corn\u2014that Is. If I asked my\nbroker to purchase $500 worth of corn\noutright for me\u2014I would get only a\nlittle over 700 bushels at the present\nprice. If I sold out at an advance of a\ncent over the price I paid, you see, I\nshould only make about $7. which\nwould hardly be enough to pay com\nmission, and the transaction would, of\ncourse, be unprofitable. Rut if I used\nmy $50V to buy on margins T could get\non the long side* of the market for 20.\n000 bushels, and be safe as long as it\ndidn\u2019t fall below the price to which 1\nwas margined. Then, in case It ad\nvanced a cent a bushel, I would make\n$200.\u201d\n\u201cOh. yes,\u201d said Mrs. Flemming. \u201cI\nsee*. Why, it Is all very simple, isn\u2019t\nit?\u201d\n\u201cExceedingly so.\u201d\n\u201cThen why' don't you go in and buy'\n20,000 bushels for margins? We could\nraise the $500.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m afraid of it. It. would be just\nour luck to buy at the top price and\nhave to sell out at a loss.\u201d\n\u201cBut the paper gives the list of\nprices every' day. I don\u2019t see why there\nshould be any\u2019 danger at all. Here is\na table which gives the opening, the\nhigh, the low, and the closing. You see\nthe high was 1 cents above the low'.\u201d\n\u201cYes.\u201d\n\u201cWell, all you would have to do\nwould be to tell your broker to buy at\nthe low and sell at the high. T don\u2019t see\nhow there would be any chance not to\ncome out ahead.\u201d\nNew Method of Dentistry\nA new method of dentistry is being\nintroduced In Paris in the form of\ntreatment of the teeth by ultra-violet\nray 8.\nSuch rays, from a mercury lamp, it\nis asserted, have the power of whiten\ning discolored teeth and sterilizing them\nin such a way that they' are not so\neasily liable to decay. The teeth to be\ntreated are Isolated from the rest,\nw'hlch are covered with a rubber shield.\nThe face, too, is protected by\u2019 a mask.\nThe teeth are then washed with oxy\ngenated w'ater and exposed for an hour\nto the direct action of the rays, y\nIt is stated that the teeth acquire\na luster like that of pearls. Two sittings\na year are recommended to keep the\nteeth In good condition.\nFigures Now Being Com\npiled Show Enormous\nTrade Strides\nSTEEL EXPORTS ARE\nSTILL INCREASING\nNew York's Automobile Statistics\nShow Enormous Increase in Num\nber of Machines Licensed\nDuring the Year\nBy HOLI.AND\nNow York, December 29.\u2014(Special.)\nNearly a year ago the friends of the\nformer speaker of the house, commonly\nknown as \u201cUncle Joe\u201d Cannon, met him\nat a farewell dinner in Washington. He\nwas the guest of honor and it was in\nrecognition quite as much of his personal\nqualities as of his career as speaker that\nthis tribute was given to him.\nLate In the evening a warm personal\nfriend of Uncle Joe had a chat with him\nrespecting business conditions. He did\nnot look out upon the future with any\nenthusiasm. He was confident that the\ncountry was entering upon an era of great\nbusiness depression and possibly of seri\nous financial disturbance. He illustrated\nhis point by making several prophetic\nstatements. Among others was the as\nsertion that within a year 50 per cent of\nthe automobiles in the United States then\nIn commission would lie out of commis\nsion and there would be a heavy falling\noff in the automobile business, which, In\nhis view, was one of the best barometers\nof prosperity in the United States.\nReport From Albany\nThe year has passed and there came\nfrom Albany a day or two ago a report\nissued from the office of Mitchell May,\nwho is secretary of state. It is as unemo\ntional and as unsentimental as any of\ntlie tables in an arithmetic. It states in\nconcise figures that in the year 1913, ex\ncepting the last two weeks, of which\nthere Is as yet no record possible, there\nhas been an increase in the number of\nmotor cars registered in the state of 34\nper cent as compared with the record of\nthe previous year. The increase over the\nrecord made in 1911 was 03 per cent. The\nstate of New York received thus far in\n1913 from fees paid by the owners or oper\nators of motor cars $1,275,000. This was\n$260,000 more than was received in 1912\nand $900,000 more than was received in\n1911.\nThat this increase was not entirely due\nto those who use motor cars exclusively\nfor pleasure driving or touring was dem\nonstrated by the fact that a little over\n13,000 commercial vehicles were licensed\nand registered in 1913 as against 8600 li\ncensed in the year 1912. These motor ve\nhicles are exclusively used for business\nThe Past and the Future\nThe gloomy prediction which the\nformer speaker of the House of Repre\nsentatives ventured to make a year ago\nand the complete refutation of It, at least\nso far as New' Y'ork state is concerned,\nthrough the authoritative statement which\nhas just been made by the secretary of\nstate Is not an exceptional case of Inac\ncurate forecast.\nA year ago many were the predictions\nof serious business reverses. It was some\ntimes said that there was likely to be a\nfalling off in our export trade in manu\nfactured products which would he ap\npalling. Some business depression has\nbeen authoritatively reported. There have\nl**en ups and downs in various parts of\nthe country. Newman Erb, who Is the\nsuccessor of Edwin Hawley in railroad\nenterprises west of the Mississippi river,\nhas recently returned from the northwest\nand has been glad to report to his\nfriends that business In that section of\ni he country is fairly prosperous. New\nYorjc bankers who have recently re\nceived reports from the south have\nlearned from these statements that busi\nness in that part of the country which\nborders the Atlantic and the eastern gulf\nhas been excellent.\nThe story of the year as a whole w'hich\nofficial statistics may tell soon after\nJanuary 1 will be found not to justify the\nvery gloomy predictions that were made\nn year ago. It is observed that business\nmen are looking more into the future\nthan they were at that time. Their eyes\nare set straight ahead.\nGrowth of Steel Exports\nThis is In part because authoritative\nstatements show how greatly, relatively\nspeaking, business has advanced In 1913,\nat least in some of the most important\nlines of trade. There is no higher au\nthority on export trad? than is the pres\nident of the United States Steel corpor\nation,' James A. Farrell. Therefore his\nrecent statement about the increase in\nour exportation of steel and iron prod\nucts is accepted without any question.\nHe said publicly a few weeks ago that\nthe exports of iron and steel from the\nUnited States have increased since 1903\nfiom 326,000 tons, round numbers, to\nnearly 3,000,000 tons, these latter figures\nbeing those of the export trade of 1912.\nThe money value >f those exports was\nIn 1903 just a million short of a hundred\nmillion dollars, whereas in 1912 It was a\nlittle over three hundred million dollars.\nAll of the authoritative reports for the\npresent year qhow that this trade has\nnot decreased, but has Increased pro\nIt's as standard as a gold\ndollar. Always abso\nW lately uniform in the\nquality of \u00bbts ripe, mel\nv low, high grade tobacco\nand perfect workman\nship.\nAll attempts at imitat\ning this wonderful ciga\nrette have ended in\nfailure. Whole coupon\nin each package.\n\nW\u2014 AC-. _A.\nCongressman's Death Ends Romance\nof Speaker Champ Clark's Daughter\nGENEVIEVE.\nCLARK.\n(Cj Qv OAV1J\nV i\u00bb-NC0\u00abO\nFriends of Miss Genevieve Clark,\ndaughter of Speaker Champ Clark, be\nlieve that the death of Representative\nIrvin S. Pepper, in Clinton, Iowa, has\n.shuttered a romance which promised to\nlead to an early engagement of mar\nriage of the young woman to Mr. Pep\nper. The death of Representative Pep\nper will cast a gloom over the debut\nMiss Clark Is lo make New Tear\u2019s Day\nIn her father\u2019s home In Washington,\nand which was to be one of the most\nnotable social affairs of the season.\nLATEST MURDER RECORD\nSHOWS NO ENCOURAGEMENT\nThe annual murder record for the\nUnited States, while showing a slight\nimprovement over previous reports,\nstill suffers by comparison, according\nto statistics of homicides compilations\nmade by Frederick L. Hoffman show\nthat there were 1344 homicides in 30\nlarge cities of this country in 1912, a\nrate of 8.1 per 100,000 of population.\nSimilar records for 1S11 were 8.4 per\n100,000. There is a corresponding de\ncrease in the relative number of sui\ncides, equivalent to 0.8 per 100,000, or\n4.1 per cent. The highest homicide rec\nord reported occurred In 1907, when the\nrate was 8.8 per 100,000, and the low'\nest rates w ere in 1891 and 1897, \\vhen\n4.2 per 100,000 was the record, says\nthe Spectator.\nOf the large American cities, Mem\nphis, Tenn., with 88 homicides, shows\na rate of 64.3 per <100,000, an increase\nover 191 i or 11.6. It is explained that\nsuburban murders are counted in w\u2019it-h\nthe city percentages.\nThe Manhattan and Bronx record\ndoes not show the same improvement\nthat the average suggests. There were\n198 homicides during the year, a rate\nof 6.8 per 100,000, or an increase of\n1.4. For the 10 years ended in 1911\nthere w*ere 1364 deaths of a homicidal\nnature, with a rate of 5.4 per 100,000.\nThe high rate of homicide shown by\nMemphis is carried out when the cities\nare taken by geographical groups. Of\nthe 30 cities cited those of the south\nern group reported 411 homicides, an\nincrease of 4.5 in its rate of 20.2 per\n100,000. Tiie eastern cities had the low\nest rate, 416, or 4.6 per 100,000, while\nthe western group showed 10.8 and the\ncentral group 8.9 per 100,000. All these\nrates showed an increase over the av\nerage for 3 0 years.\nOf special interest in the tabulations\nis the inclusion of a record kept by\nthe Chicago Tribune of the causes of\nhomicides from 1908 to 1912. Accord\ning to this, 48.9 per cent of the whole\nnumber was caused by quarrels, while\nunknown causes were responsible for\n14.1 per cent. Liquor is given as the\ncause of 9.6 per cent of the total, while\nmurders by highwaymen caused 8.5 per\ncent of the deaths. Jealousy, incidental\nly, was responsible for the same per\ncentage.\nTo Reading, Pa., is given the distinc\ntion of having no homicides committed\nwithin its limits in 1912, while in Phil\nadelphia there were only 23 homi\ncides, a rate of 1.4 per 100,000. For the\n10 years ending in 3 911 Hartford, Conn.,\nhad the lowest number of homicide\ndeaths, 26, although Milwaukee showed\nthe lowest rate, 1.9 per 100,000. The\nlargest number of deaths from homi\ncide iq 10 years is shown by Chicago,\nwith a total of 1770.\nIn support of its comment on the\nunfavorable record of this country com\nparisons are made with the homicide\nrecords in foreign cities. In Italy, es\npecially, wrhere it Is generally as\nsumed that human life is held cheap\nly. the rate for the latest year avail\nable. 1910, is 3.4 per 100,000. A flve\nyearaver&ge shows a rate of 3.9. In\nother words, to every 100 homicides\nin the United States there are only GG\nin Italy.\nLondon, including only the city\nproper, shows a five-year average of\n1.31 por 100,000. as compared wrIth the\nsame average for Now York of 6.0. In\nParis in 1910 a rate of 3.6 was record\ned. The city of Copenhagen, Denmark,\nis shown to be the safest European\nj city, with a record in 1910 of only one\nI homicide and a five-year rat\u00a9 of 0.45.\nportionately as largely ns the increase i\nof any of the previous years over tha\nnext preceding one. Very likely the offi\ncial report from Washington in January\nwill show a proportionately greater rate\nof increase in 1913.\nNo one can talk with some of those\nwho have part in great undertakings\nwithout sharing the enthusiasm these men\nfee! when they speak of the immediate fu\nture of business, industrial, commercial\nand agricultural, in t.he United States.\nAlmost all these men find it impossible\ntj voice their thought in equivalent lan\nguage. James Stillman, who has been\nsojourning for a year or two in Paris,\nbut who keeps daily informed of con\nditions in the United States, said while\nupon his most recent visit to thi* coun\ntry that the future possibilities evin cer\ntainties of business of all kinds in the\nUnited States simply stagger the lmagi\nnation of the man who contempiate.4 our\nfuture.\nThedore Vail's Views\nTn a recent conversation with Theo\ndore N. Vail, president of the Am^ricaft\nTelegraph and Telephone company, ha\nwith dramatic gesture, tried to express\nmore perfectly his thought than he could\ndo in words. He looked ahead with\namazement to a time of industrial, com\nmercial and agricultural activity and\nespecially to the Investment of capital In\n\\ery high development of American re\nsources. He said that our people at this\ntime do not realize what is in store for\nthe United States in the way of corn\nmenial, industrial and business develop\nment of all kinds.\nThere is the same Idea behind these\npredictions which Mr. Morgan had in\nmind when he stated sententiously that\nhe man who \u201cis a bear on the United\nStates will go broke.\" The thought was\nnot original with him, for it has been\ndiscovered since Mr. Morgan\u2019s death that\none of the first lessons which his father,\nJunius S. Morgan, taught the son was\nthe certainty of stupendous growth in ma\nterial prosperity in the United States, the\nlike of which, the senior Morgan states,\ncould not be read in any history of civi\nlized nations. With a changed attitude\nof public men, toward business, and of\nbusiness toward the people with a sin\ncere desire to facilitate business activi\nties along wise paths, which is now re\ngarded as having been unquestionably be\nhind recent national legislation, and with\ntho opening of the Panama canal to navi\ngation within a few months there seems\ntc be no reason why there should not be\ndiscerned in the year 1911 the beginnings\nof the new\u2019 era w\u2019hicii the ablest of our\nbusiness men have forecast.\nInsatiability\nFrom the Cincinnati Enquirer.\nPresident Wilson told a little group of\nPrinceton visitors a Thanksgiving story.\n\u201cThey who complain this year,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201care as insatiable as the little boy\nat the Thanksgiving party.\n\u201cTo this little boy. at the party\u2019s end\na lady said:\n\u2018Well, did you have a good time?\u2019\n'No'm.'\n'Why, how was that?'\nI 'They told me to eat as much as 1\nwanted, and I\u2014I couldn\u2019t.\u2019\nRAILROAD OWNERSHIP\nPresent Generation of Railroad Men\nVigorously Opposed to the Idea\nRailroad problems, of various kinds,\nnotably the reckless policy that has\nproved so disastrous to the New Haven\ncompany, have, not unnaturally, given\nrise to more or less vague recent talk\nabout the desirability of government\nownership of our railroads, says the Phi],\nadelphta Record. This Is too vast a sub\nJect to be discussed In any off-hand way,\nand It Is by no means llkelq that It will\nbe brought actually before the people\nfor decision for many years. In the mean\ntime we are certain to have a great\namount of arguing pro and con, with\nmore than the usual looseness of ex\npression. T he present generation of rail\nroad men are vigorously opposed to the\nIdea, and with good reason. The Railway\nAge Gazette. In a discussion of the ques\ntion, presents some strong objections t.j\ngovernment ownership, among which are\nthese:\nith all their faults, the management\nasul operation of the railways of the\nUnited States have been and are such, as\ncompared with the way other public ami\nprivate affairs have been handled in this\ncountry, and as compared with the way\ntha railways of other countries have been\nmanaged, as to render It practicable to\nmake an extremely strong case for pri\nvate ownership and management. To\nthe counts that there has been much un\nfair discrimination and that their acci\ndent record Is had our railways must\nplead guilty. But regulation has greatly\nreduced the discrimination; and the\nstatistics of the railways of our own\nand other countries demonstrate that\nthere Is no connection between the form\nof ownership of railways and their safety.\nOn all other counts In the Indictment that\ntheir critics draw against them our rail\nways can make a better defense than\ncould any other railways In the world.\nTheir capitalization per mile can he\nshown to he much less than that of any\nother railways that can fairly he com\npared with them. They can he shown to\npay the highest wages of any railways In\nthe world, not only absolutely, hut also\nin proportion to the cost of living In this\ncountry. It ean be shown that. In spite\nof this, they make as low passenger rates\nas anv other railways having a rorre\nspending density of traffic, nnd the low\nest freight rates In the world, except per\nhaps, In Japan, where, of course, wag\u00b0r\nare extremely low; and that In propor\ntion to wages and prices In the country\nwhere they are charged, their passenger\nrates are among the lowest, nnd their\nfreight rates much the lowest In the\nworld.\nThat they are able to do those things\nran he shown to be due to the fact that\nthey have been developed and are ope\nrated with skill and economy that are the.\nwonder, the admiration, and the envy of\nrailway managers throughout the world\nThe onlv country where the efficiency\nand economy with which American rail\nways are operated Is not conceded and\napreclated Is the United States'\nit can be shown that In no other country\nOvercoats Underpriced\n20% At Porter\u2019s\nOur entire stock of fine Overcoats, made by Rogers Peet Co. and Schloss Bros.,\nin a vide range, embracing every good style and fabric foremost in this season\u2019s\nchoosing.\n$18 Overcoats 14.40\n$20 Overcoats 16.00\n$25 Overcoats $20.00\n$30 Overcoats $24,00\n$35 Overcoats $28.00\n$40 Overcoats $32.00\n$45 Overcoats $36.00\n$50 Overcoats $40.00\nl/s On On Boys Suits and Overcoats\nOur entire stock of Boys\u2019 Suits and Overcoats at 20 per cent discount.. Suits in\nNorfolk and double breasted styles, with full lined knickerbockers. Overcoats are in\nmany smart models, with shawl or regular collars, belted or plain back. Any of them at\n20% Discount\nw\n1922-1924 First Avenue \u201cIn the Heart of Birmingham\u201d\nP\u2014 I i \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014mm\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u25a0\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014i^\u2014\u2014\u2014W\u2014\u25a0\u2014\u2014\u25a0WW\u2014\u2014\u2014\u00bb\nBy the S. S. CLEVELAND GSRS) H\nLeave NEW YORK, JAN. 15, 1914\nCOST includes shore excursions and all necessary expenses.\nExcellent accommodations also available on this cruise for passage to MADEIRA,\nSPAIN, ALGIERS, ITALY and EGYPT only, cost of shore excursions included.\nWrite for booklet containing full information Cui'IEJP\nHAMBURG-AMERICAN LINE M\nis the service rendered by the railways\nany better, or perhaps so good, consider\ning the conditions under which it is ren\ndered. Tt can he shown that while most\nstate railways fail to earn the interest\non the investment in them, leaving a de\nficit to be raised by taxation of the pub\nlic, the railways of the United States re\nturn to the public in taxes almost 1 per\ncent of their gross earnings, or about\n$110,000,000 annually. Finally, and most\nimportant of all, it can be shown that in\nevery democratic country where the pub\nlic owns the railways the employes con\nstantly use their political Influences hh\nvoters to get concessions from the man\nagements, and that the transfer to the\ngovernment service of 1.700,000 employes\nof the railways of this country, most >r\nthem organized into strong unions, prob\nably would have the most baneful ef\nfects on politics, if, indeed, it would njt\nwork the overthrow of democratic gov\nernment.\nThe Side-Swiping Feather\nIf a man tried to wear snowshoes in the\nsubway he would be mobbed by the first\npassengers who tripped over his pro\nlonged feet, says the New York Tribune.\nSo, too, If he tried to go to work In a\nwashtub or upon a hobby horse or play\ning the slide trombone. Space is scape\non this crowded little ball of earth, and\nwe all are obliged not to Infringe upon\nour neighbors' rights. All except the\nwoman with the side-swiping feather, that\nis. She bears a charmed life. Because\nshe is a woman or because hats are hats\nshe goes her way tickling and eye-poking\nand temper-destroying, without ever ga\nting so much as a harsh word\u2014to say\nnothing of a black eye or a kick In the\nshins. What we wish to know Is -and,\nas can be seen, we speak with all th\nintense bitterness of personal injury why\ndo not some of our mighty constitutional\nlawyers discover a means for abating\nthis nuisance? L4fe, liberty and the pur\nsuit of happiness, for Instance. What do\nthey amount to while these ticklers\nwave? Must freemen, Insulted and over\nborne, wait meekly until the fashions\nchange? Or can they throw themselves\nInto the breach and bite, chop or yank\noff these invasions of a sacred, inborn\nright? What Patrick Henry will dare to\nreply.\nSkin a Human Mosaic\nFrom the Chicago Journal.\nHuman cuticle reacts peculiarly to j\nstimuli. The makers of billiard halls test\nthe smoothness of the finished article by\nrubbing it against the cheek. Certain\nareas of the tongu^e are very sensitive to\ndifferent flavors, while about an Inch\nfrom the tip is a little patch which is\nthe precise spot to dump objectionable\nmedicine, for in that region the sense of\ntaste is absent. If one marks on the bl\neeps of the arm a little space, and tests\nIt with the warmed head of a pin, soma\nspots will feel Just pressure, others\nwarmth and pressure. And if one has a\nlittle red ink on the. pin he can mark\nout just, where these \"warm spots\u201d are.\nIn fact. th.> cut lei** seems a mosaic of\n\"warm\u201d and \"cold\u201d spots. And there\nis sb1<1 to he a. place above the knee*\nwhore one can drive a pin without pain.\nTransfer the\nS lobe^V&r t> icke\nSafeguarded Way\nYou simply move folders from the active file to the storage case;\nthat is all there is to transferring by the Globe-Wernicke safeguard\nmethod. \\rou are saved the expense of new guides, since a feature of\nthe safeguard method indexes the transferred papers without extra cost.\nGlobe-Wernicke Transfer Cases are stoutly made, have roller hear\nings and like Globe-Wernicke Filing Devices, are sectional. We are\nprepared to supply your needs immediately from stock.\nWe carry at all times a large stock of Filing Cabinets and supplies\nj in the way of folders, guides, record cards, etc., for your new year\u2019s\nbusiness.\nBen M. Jacobs Bros.\nOFFICE OUTFITTERS\n1911-13 Third Avenue","height":"27828","width":"19668"}}
